                            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26042390/git-add-asterisk-vs-git-add-period/26042516#comment40797252_26042516",
                            "body": "So would there every be a reason to use the asterisk? Is there any advantage to using it instead of a period? Or vice versa? I&#39;m sure I saw it in a tutorial. I wouldn&#39;t have known to use it otherwise. I&#39;m not much of a command line guy (as you&#39;ve undoubtedly guessed)."
                        },
                        {
                            "owner": {
                                "account_id": 2818342,
                                "reputation": 303386,
                                "user_id": 2422776,
                                "user_type": "registered",
                                "display_name": "Mureinik"
                            },
                            "reply_to_user": {
                                "account_id": 466310,
                                "reputation": 2870,
                                "user_id": 870980,
                                "user_type": "registered",
                                "accept_rate": 62,
                                "display_name": "Tyler Youngblood"
                            },
                            "edited": false,
                            "score": 6,
                            "creation_date": 1411663776,
                            "post_id": 26042516,
                            "comment_id": 40798008,
                            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26042390/git-add-asterisk-vs-git-add-period/26042516#comment40798008_26042516",
                            "body": "<code>*</code> avoids hidden files (i.e., files that their name begins with a <code>.</code>). In any event, if you aren&#39;t adding specific files, I&#39;d just use <code>git add -u</code> (or <code>git add -A</code> if you&#39;re creating new files)."
                        },
