                            "creation_date": 1602606627,
                            "post_id": 26042555,
                            "comment_id": 113771325,
                            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26042390/git-add-asterisk-vs-git-add-period/26042555#comment113771325_26042555",
                            "body": "The answer is a bit confusing, since the former method says &quot;all files in the current directory&quot; whereas the latter says &quot;the entire directory recursively&quot;. One could think that the former (i.e. <code>add * </code>) only adds files (not folders) in the first level, but not recursively."
                        }
                    ],
                    "owner": {
                        "account_id": 1045530,
                        "reputation": 5191,
                        "user_id": 1050610,
                        "user_type": "registered",
                        "display_name": "Denis"
                    },
                    "comment_count": 11,
                    "is_accepted": true,
                    "score": 210,
                    "last_activity_date": 1559867451,
                    "last_edit_date": 1559867451,
                    "creation_date": 1411659429,
                    "answer_id": 26042555,
                    "question_id": 26042390,
                    "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26042390/git-add-asterisk-vs-git-add-period/26042555#26042555",
                    "body": "<p><code>add *</code> means add all files in the current directory, except for files whose name begin with a dot. This is your shell functionality and Git only ever receives a list of files.</p>\n\n<p><code>add .</code> has no special meaning in your shell, and thus Git adds the entire directory recursively, which is almost the same, but including files whose names begin with a dot.</p>\n"
                },
                {
                    "owner": {
                        "account_id": 1492165,
                        "reputation": 1217,
                        "user_id": 1399018,
                        "user_type": "registered",
                        "accept_rate": 86,
                        "display_name": "codingdave"
                    },
                    "comment_count": 0,
                    "is_accepted": false,
                    "score": 8,
                    "last_activity_date": 1504189847,
                    "last_edit_date": 1504189847,
                    "creation_date": 1473167583,
                    "answer_id": 39349920,
                    "question_id": 26042390,
                    "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26042390/git-add-asterisk-vs-git-add-period/39349920#39349920",
                    "body": "<p>Using the dot <code>.</code>  in the shell usually means \"the current directory\".</p>\n\n<p>When you use the asterisk <code>*</code> on a shell a feature called <code>file-globbing</code> is utilized. E.g. on bash the function <code>glob()</code> is doing just that. The manpage for glob (<code>man 7 glob</code>) states:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><strong>DESCRIPTION</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>Long ago, in UNIX V6, there was a program /etc/glob that would expand \nwildcard patterns.  Soon afterward this became a shell built-in.\nThese days there is also a library routine glob(3) that will perform this \nfunction for a user program.\n</code></pre>\n  \n  <p><strong>Wildcard matching</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>A string is a wildcard pattern  if it contains one of the characters '?', '*' or '['. \n</code></pre>\n  \n  <p><strong>Globbing</strong> </p>\n\n<pre><code>Globbing is the operation that expands a wildcard pattern \ninto the list of pathnames matching the pattern.\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>That means when you pass arguments to any program on the commandline that contain <code>'?'</code>, <code>'*'</code>or <code>'['</code>, first globbing expands the wildcard pattern into a list of files and then gives these files as an argument to the program itself.</p>\n\n<p>The difference in meaning between <code>'git add .'</code> and <code>'git add *'</code>is clearly described by <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/26042555/1399018\" title=\"Denis\">Denis</a>:</p>\n\n<p><code>git add</code> expects a list of files to be added. In the above example the shell expands <code>*</code> or <code>.</code> respectively and gives the result as a parameter to git add. Now the difference is that with <code>git add .</code> git will expand to the current directory whereas <code>git add *</code> triggers file globbing and such expands to all files and directories that do not start with a dot.  </p>\n"
                },
                {
